comment_data.body:
My tentative plan for Vimspector (appreciate any and all nitpicking about it), is as follows:

The author originally only cared about supporting Vim, and Neovim support was an afterthought driven by popular request. He's doing a great job adding support for it, but some of the features he'd need aren't stable yet.

@bfredl To your point, we should focus on first rearchitecting its interface to use as much as possible from `vim/lsp/until.lua`. Then, we can focus on porting the core; it can be a line-by-line, function-by-function, port, as long as it supports the same protocol and eventually holds up to a more rigorous testing strategy.

@justinmk Does this sound agreeable to you?

@puremourning LOL. I know you're really close to rolling out support for Neovim, but:
- Some of the interface elements could be better if we could reuse the elements that the LSP module provides
- Your core is in Python 3, so there's no first-class support

@puremourning Like I said, my biggest problem with Vimspector is that it's in Python, i.e. a second-class language. I wouldn't want a Python dependency if I was coding in, say, Java or Go.

@bfredl I'll definitely see this through up to designing a roadmap of tasks on a PR that'll get the interface to where I'd want it (i.e. using `util.lua` and generalizing the same to a "foreign protocol interface" of something like that).

Beyond that, I unfortunately don't know how much time I'll have, especially if this project goes as big as the LSP project (we'd need more contributors in that case). If I end up realizing that this is more work than I myself can handle, I'll do my best to make it easier for other like-minded contributors to take over the PR.
